:\"67478dad-99af-468c-98e7-913773b40f8d\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01ALvqG2Kcy47XvdJjQvJsj1\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Review 01\\n     2→\\n     3→> Status: pending-dev\\n     4→> Date: 2026-03-10\\n     5→> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n     6→> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n     7→\\n     8→## Previous Review Status\\n     9→No previous reviews.\\n    10→\\n    11→## New Findings\\n    12→\\n    13→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    14→\\n    15→- **[Plan Step 3, line 90-91]** `strat.LoadSessionState` does not exist. The plan calls `strat.LoadSessionState(ctx, sessionID)` on the `ManualCommitStrategy` receiver, but this method is **private** (`loadSessionState`, lowercase). The existing `attach.go` code at line 159 correctly uses the **package-level** function `strategy.LoadSessionState(ctx, sessionID)`. The plan must use `strategy.LoadSessionState` instead of `strat.LoadSessionState`.\\n    16→\\n    17→- **[Plan Step 3, line 113-114]** Same issue repeated in the IDLE transition replacement block. `strategy.LoadSessionState` is already correct there, but this block also uses `strategy.TransitionAndLog` and `strategy.SaveSessionState` which are package-level functions -- these are fine. However, note the inconsistency: the plan uses `strat.LoadSessionState` in one place (Step 3 code block 2, line 90) and `strategy.LoadSessionState` in another (Step 3 code block 4, line 114). The first is wrong, the second is correct.\\n    18→\\n    19→- **[Plan Step 3]** Missing state fields in post-condensation update. When `CondenseSessionByID` updates state after condensation (see `manual_commit_condensation.go:817-824`), it also resets `AttributionBaseCommit`, `PromptAttributions`, and `PendingPromptAttribution`. The plan's Step 3 replacement block only sets `StepCount`, `CheckpointTranscriptStart`, and `LastCheckpointID`, omitting these three fields. This will leave stale attribution data in the session state, which could cause incorrect attribution in subsequent checkpoints.\\n    20→\\n    21→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    22→\\n    23→- **[Plan Step 3]** Condensation failure handling is inconsistent. If `CondenseSession` fails, the plan logs a warning (line 97-98) but does NOT return an error, letting execution continue. However, `condenseResult` will be `nil` in that case, which means the checkpoint ID output is skipped (the `if condenseResult != nil` guard on line 105 handles this). But the IDLE transition replacement block still runs `finalState.StepCount = 0` only `if condenseResult != nil`, which means a failed condensation leaves the step count intact. This is reasonable behavior, but the plan should explicitly document the intent: \\\"if condensation fails, the shadow branch checkpoint is still valid and the session state is left as-is for the next condensation attempt.\\\" Currently it just silently continues without explanation.\\n    24→\\n    25→- **[Plan Step 3]** The plan does not call `cleanupShadowBranchIfUnused` after condensation. `CondenseSessionByID` (lines 831-837) performs shadow branch cleanup as a best-effort step after condensation. Since the plan is essentially inlining `CondenseSessionByID` logic into `attach.go`, it should also call this cleanup or document why it is intentionally skipped. Without it, shadow branches accumulate for attached sessions.\\n    26→\\n    27→- **[Plan Step 3]** The `condenseResult` variable is used after the error check but is declared in a scope where `err` shadows the outer `err`. The plan's code generates `checkpointID`, opens `repo`, loads `updatedState`, and calls `CondenseSession` -- all reusing `err`. Since the condensation error is non-fatal (warning only), the `err` variable from `CondenseSession` will be non-nil on failure but the function continues. The next error assignment (in the IDLE transition block) would then shadow it. This works but is fragile. Consider using a distinct variable name like `condenseErr` for the condensation call.\\n    28→\\n    29→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    30→\\n    31→- **[Plan Step 3]** Consider using `CondenseSessionByID` directly instead of inlining its logic. The existing `CondenseSessionByID` method already handles: generating the checkpoint ID, opening the repo, loading session state, calling `CondenseSession`, updating all state fields (including attribution), and cleaning up shadow branches. Calling `strat.CondenseSessionByID(ctx, sessionID)` would be significantly simpler and less error-prone than reproducing all that logic in `attach.go`. The only downside is that `CondenseSessionByID` returns `error` not `*CondenseResult`, so you would not have the checkpoint ID to print. Two options:\\n    32→  1. Add a variant like `CondenseSessionByIDWithResult` that returns `(*CondenseResult, error)`.\\n    33→  2. After calling `CondenseSessionByID`, read the `LastCheckpointID` from the updated session state.\\n    34→  Option 2 is zero new API surface and works immediately since `CondenseSessionByID` already sets `state.LastCheckpointID`.\\n    35→\\n    36→- **[Plan Test]** The proposed test `TestAttach_OutputContainsCheckpointID` is essentially a duplicate of `TestAttach_Success` with the addition of a regex check. Consider extending `TestAttach_Success` with the checkpoint ID assertion instead of adding a separate test, to avoid code duplication across nearly identical test setups.\\n    37→\\n    38→- **[Plan Test]** The test does not verify that condensation actually persisted data to the `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch. Adding a check (e.g., verify the branch exists and has a commit, or that the session state's `LastCheckpointID` is set) would increase confidence that the end-to-end flow works, not just that a string appears in output.\\n    39→\\n    40→### Praise\\n    41→\\n    42→- Good use of the existing `id.Generate()` function -- the plan correctly identifies the right package and function signature.\\n    43→- The plan correctly identifies where in `runAttach` to insert the condensation logic (after `SaveStep`, before the IDLE transition).\\n    44→- Using `condenseResult.CheckpointID` rather than the locally generated `checkpointID` for output is a good defensive pattern (ensures what was actually persisted is what gets printed).\\n    45→\\n    46→## Summary\\n    47→\\n    48→- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n    49→- **Key concerns:**\\n    50→  1. `strat.LoadSessionState` does not exist as a public method -- this will cause a compile error.\\n    51→  2. Missing attribution state reset fields will cause subtle bugs.\\n    52→  3. The plan inlines ~30 lines of logic that `CondenseSessionByID` already encapsulates. Strongly recommend using the existing method (with option 2 from Suggestions to get the checkpoint ID) to avoid reimplementing and potentially drifting from the canonical condensation flow.\\n    53→- **Estimated effort to address feedback:** Small -- if the suggestion to use `CondenseSessionByID` is adopted, the implementation becomes significantly simpler (maybe 10 lines instead of 30). If inlining is preferred, fixing the compile error and adding the missing state fields is ~15 minutes of work.\\n    54→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"f1715249-48f3-4129-b024-205be38008d8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-12T21:02:09.878Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"abd9c75d4ca4f20c1\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01N5f6K5tSoQg7hwaVTodhki\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01CSrNk4CarZebr4jS4rwkA8\",\"uuid\":\"59f1560f-ffd9-4cab-ba68-a128bc87ae82\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-12T21:02:10.332Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/ninawork/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"61b0a478-d835-45a6-936a-9d30f7ba786c\",\"version\":\"2.1.74\",\"gitBranch\":\"attach-session-id\",\"slug\":\"fancy-dreaming-biscuit\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"59f1560f-ffd9-4cab-ba68-a128bc87ae82\",\"isSidechain\":fals