om review-01: Shadow branch cleanup missing - FIXED (handled by `CondenseSessionByID`)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: `condenseErr` naming suggestion - FIXED (plan uses `condenseErr`)\\n\\nThe plan has been substantially improved since review-01. All critical and important issues from the previous review have been addressed.\\n\\n## Spec Coverage Check\\n\\nAll six fixes from the spec are covered in the plan:\\n\\n| Spec Fix | Plan Task | Status |\\n|----------|-----------|--------|\\n| Fix 1: Write prompt.txt | Task 2 | Covered |\\n| Fix 2: Gemini prompt extraction | Task 1 | Covered |\\n| Fix 3: Token usage | Task 3 | Covered |\\n| Fix 4: Model name extraction | Task 5 | Covered |\\n| Fix 5: Session metrics (turn count + duration) | Tasks 4 + 6 | Covered |\\n| Fix 6: Attribution (verify existing) | Not a separate task | Spec says \\\"no code change needed\\\" - OK |\\n\\nNo missing spec items.\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n1. **[Task 6, line 590] `estimateSessionDuration` parses timestamp from `line.Message` -- but timestamp is a TOP-LEVEL field, not inside `message`.**\\n\\n   The plan's implementation does:\\n   ```go\\n   if err := json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &ts); err != nil || ts.Timestamp == \\\"\\\" {\\n   ```\\n\\n   But in Claude Code JSONL, `timestamp` is at the same level as `type`, `uuid`, `message`:\\n   ```\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{...},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\",\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"2026-01-01T10:00:00.000Z\\\"}\\n   ```\\n\\n   The `transcript.Line` struct (`transcript/types.go:22-27`) only captures `type`, `role`, `uuid`, `message` -- it does NOT have a `Timestamp` field. So `line.Message` contains the inner message object (e.g., `{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"hi\\\"}`), which does NOT contain `timestamp`.\\n\\n   This means `json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &ts)` will always produce an empty timestamp, and the function will always return 0.\\n\\n   **Fix:** You cannot use the parsed `transcript.Line` structs for timestamp extraction. Instead, parse each raw JSONL line directly (before the `transcript.ParseFromBytes` call), similar to how `claudecode/lifecycle.go:268-274` does it -- unmarshal the raw line bytes, not `line.Message`. Example:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   func estimateSessionDuration(data []byte) int64 {\\n       var first, last time.Time\\n       for _, rawLine := range bytes.Split(data, []byte(\\\"\\\\n\\\")) {\\n           rawLine = bytes.TrimSpace(rawLine)\\n           if len(rawLine) == 0 {\\n               continue\\n           }\\n           var entry struct {\\n               Timestamp string `json:\\\"timestamp\\\"`\\n           }\\n           if json.Unmarshal(rawLine, &entry) != nil || entry.Timestamp == \\\"\\\" {\\n               continue\\n           }\\n           t, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339Nano, entry.Timestamp)\\n           if err != nil {\\n               continue\\n           }\\n           if first.IsZero() {\\n               first = t\\n           }\\n           last = t\\n       }\\n       if first.IsZero() || !last.After(first) {\\n           return 0\\n       }\\n       return last.Sub(first).Milliseconds()\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This matches the existing pattern in `claudecode/lifecycle.go:261-279`.\\n\\n2. **[Task 6, line 533] Test data for `estimateSessionDuration` has timestamp at the wrong level too.**\\n\\n   The test data is:\\n   ```\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"hi\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\",\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"2026-01-01T10:00:00.000Z\\\"}\\n   ```\\n\\n   The timestamp IS at the top level here (correct for the raw line), but the implementation parses `line.Message` (wrong). So the test would actually FAIL even with this test data if the implementation uses `line.Message`. The test data is correct for the raw-line-parsing approach recommended above, but contradicts the implementation code in the plan.\\n\\n3. **[Task 1, line 94 and Task 4, line 380] `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts` returns `([]string, error)`, not just `[]string`.**\\n\\n   The spec (line 73) has:\\n   ```go\\n   if prompts := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); len(prompts) > 0 {\\n   ```\\n\\n   The plan (line 94) has:\\n   ```go\\n   if prompts, gemErr := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); gemErr == nil && len(prompts) > 0 {\\n   ```\\n\\n   The plan's version is correct. However, in Task 4 (`countUserTurns`, line 380), the plan has:\\n   ```go\\n   if prompts, gemErr := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); gemErr == nil {\\n       return len(prompts)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This is correct Go. The spec's version would not compile. The plan correctly handles the error return in both places. No action needed -- noting this for completeness as the spec has a bug here that the plan already fixed.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n4. **[Task 4, lines 362-385] `countUserTurns` double-counts tool_result lines.**\\n\\n   In Claude Code JSONL transcripts, tool result messages have `\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\"` at the top level. For example, from the existing test in `attach_test.go:75-76`:\\n   ```\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_result\\\",\\\"tool_use_id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"wrote file\\\"}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"uuid-3\\\"}\\n   ```\\n\\n   This line has `line.Type == transcript.TypeUser` (i.e., `\\\"user\\\"`), so `countUserTurns` will count it as a turn. A transcript with 1 real user prompt and 5 tool calls would report 6 turns instead of 1.\\n\\n   The spec (Fix 5) mentions \\\"Count lines with `transcript.TypeUser`\\\" without addressing this. The spec also mentions using `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts` length for Gemini, but does not mention filtering for JSONL.\\n\\n   **Fix:** Filter out tool_result lines. Check if the message content is an array containing `tool_result` blocks:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   for _, line := range lines {\\n       if line.Type == transcript.TypeUser {\\n           // Skip tool_result messages -- they have type \\\"user\\\" but are not user turns\\n           var msg struct {\\n               Content []struct {\\n                   Type string `json:\\\"type\\\"`\\n               } `json:\\\"content\\\"`\\n           }\\n           if json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &msg) == nil && len(msg.Content) > 0 {\\n               isToolResult := true\\n               for _, c := range msg.Content {\\n                   if c.Type != \\\"tool_result\\\" {\\n                       isToolResult = false\\n                       break\\n                   }\\n               }\\n               if isToolResult {\\n                   continue\\n               }\\n           }\\n           count++\\n       }\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   Alternatively, reuse `extractTextFromMessage` -- if it returns non-empty, it is a real user prompt (since `extractTextFromMessage` looks for string content or text blocks, not tool_result blocks).\\n\\n5. **[Task 4, lines 309-313] Test data for `TestAttach_SetsSessionTurnCount` does not exercise tool_result scenario.**\\n\\n   The test uses a clean 2-user-message / 2-assistant-message transcript. It will pass even with the double-counting bug because there are no tool_result lines. Add a test case with tool_result lines to catch the double-counting:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   transcriptContent := `{\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"first prompt\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\"}\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_use\\\",\\\"id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"Write\\\",\\\"input\\\":{}}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"a1\\\"}\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_result\\\",\\\"tool_use_id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"ok\\\"}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u2\\\"}\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"second prompt\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u3\\\"}\\n   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"done\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"a2\\\"}\\n   `\\n   // Expected: 2 turns (not 3)\\n   ```\\n\\n6. **[Task 6, line 596-599] Redundant time format parsing.**\\n\\n   The plan parses timestamps with `time.RFC3339Nano` first, then falls back to `\\\"2006-01-02T15:04:05.000Z\\\"`. But `time.RFC3339Nano` already handles the `.000Z` format (the Go docs confirm RFC3339Nano = `\\\"2006-01-02T15:04:05.999999999Z07:00\\\"`, which matches millisecond timestamps). The existing codebase in `claudecode/lifecycle.go:274-276` falls back to `time.RFC3339` (without nano), not a custom format. Use the same pattern as the existing code:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   t, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339Nano, entry.Timestamp)\\n   if err != nil {\\n       t, err = time.Parse(time.RFC3339, entry.Timestamp)\\n       if err != nil {\\n           continue\\n       }\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n7. **[Task 2, line 152] Test checks the wrong path for `prompt.txt`.**\\n\\n   The test checks `filepath.Join(tmpDir, \\\".entire\\\", \\\"sessions\\\", sessionID, \\\"prompt.txt\\\")`. But `paths.SessionMetadataDirFromSessionID` returns a path under `.entire/metadata/` (as documented in the CLAUDE.md metadata structure section), not `.entire/sessions/`. Verify the actual path returned by `paths.SessionMetadataDirFromSessionID` and update the test accordingly, or the test will always fail with \\\"prompt.txt not found\\\" for the wrong reason.\\n\\n8. **[Task 5, line 429] Test data includes `model` inside `message` -- verify this is where Claude Code actually puts it.**\\n\\n   The test has `\\\"model\\\":\\\"claude-sonnet-4-20250514\\\"` inside the `message` JSON object. The implementation parses `line.Message` for a `model` field, which would work if the model is indeed inside `message`. However, Claude's API returns `model` at the top level of the API response, not nested inside the message body. Whether Claude Code's JSONL logger writes it inside `message` or at the JSONL line top level depends on how the agent serializes its transcript. If `model` is at the top level (like `timestamp`), then parsing `line.Message` would fail. Check a real Claude Code transcript to confirm. If `model` is at the line level, you would need the same raw-line-parsing approach as for timestamps.\\n\\n9. **[General] Consider extracting a `parseRawJSONLLines` helper.** Both `estimateSessionDuration` (raw line parsing for timestamps) and potentially `extractModelFromTranscript` (if model is top-level) need to split raw JSONL data and unmarshal each line. A small helper that yields raw line bytes would reduce duplication.\\n\\n10. **[Task 3, line 267] `CalculateTokenUsage` signature has 5 parameters but plan passes 4.**\\n\\n    The spec (line 90) shows:\\n    ```go\\n    agent.CalculateTokenUsage(ctx, ag, transcriptData, 0)\\n    ```\\n\\n    But the actual signature (`agent/token_usage.go:13`) is:\\n    ```go\\n    func CalculateTokenUsage(ctx context.Context, ag Agent, transcriptData []byte, transcriptLinesAtStart int, subagentsDir string) *TokenUsage\\n    ```\\n\\n    The plan (line 267) correctly passes 5 args:\\n    ```go\\n    agent.CalculateTokenUsage(logCtx, ag, transcriptData, 0, \\\"\\\")\\n    ```\\n\\n    The spec has a bug (4 args). The plan is correct. No action needed -- noting for completeness.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- The plan has been thoroughly revised since review-01. All previous critical issues are resolved. The adoption of `CondenseSessionByID` (via `condenseAndFinalizeSession`) is a much cleaner approach than the original inlined condensation logic.\\n- Good test-driven development structure throughout -- each task writes a failing test first, then implements.\\n- The Gemini fallback pattern (try JSONL first, fall back to Gemini JSON) is consistent and well-structured 